1
00:00:00,060 --> 00:00:02,130
- So the stock market will crash.

2
00:00:02,130 --> 00:00:03,990
It's happened time and time again.

3
00:00:03,990 --> 00:00:05,850
This is the scary truth.

4
00:00:05,850 --> 00:00:08,340
However, it doesn't
have to be a bad thing.

5
00:00:08,340 --> 00:00:10,200
As long as you are properly prepared,

6
00:00:10,200 --> 00:00:12,060
you can benefit from the chaos.

7
00:00:12,060 --> 00:00:14,550
I've been investing
for more than 35 years,

8
00:00:14,550 --> 00:00:16,470
and as you can imagine during that time,

9
00:00:16,470 --> 00:00:18,870
I've experienced lots of these crashes.

10
00:00:18,870 --> 00:00:20,400
However, I always seem

11
00:00:20,400 --> 00:00:22,950
to come out the other side
wealthier than before.

12
00:00:22,950 --> 00:00:24,720
So today I wanna share the knowledge

13
00:00:24,720 --> 00:00:26,040
that has helped me make millions

14
00:00:26,040 --> 00:00:28,050
through multiple market crashes.

15
00:00:28,050 --> 00:00:29,910
By understanding these strategies,

16
00:00:29,910 --> 00:00:32,160
you can spot the warning signs of a crash

17
00:00:32,160 --> 00:00:34,050
and use them to your advantage.

18
00:00:34,050 --> 00:00:36,630
So how common is a market crash?

19
00:00:36,630 --> 00:00:39,900
Well, there are three different
types of market decline.

20
00:00:39,900 --> 00:00:42,150
First is the most common type of decline,

21
00:00:42,150 --> 00:00:44,100
a market correction.

22
00:00:44,100 --> 00:00:48,300
This is defined as at least a
10% drop from a recent high.

23
00:00:48,300 --> 00:00:50,640
These can be caused by various factors,

24
00:00:50,640 --> 00:00:52,590
but think of it as the stock market,

25
00:00:52,590 --> 00:00:54,960
realizing it's getting a bit expensive

26
00:00:54,960 --> 00:00:57,090
and cutting back prices.

27
00:00:57,090 --> 00:00:58,470
On average, these have happened

28
00:00:58,470 --> 00:01:01,440
around every 1.2 years since 1980.

29
00:01:01,440 --> 00:01:04,950
The second most common type
of decline is a bear market.

30
00:01:04,950 --> 00:01:06,960
Now, you know when
you're in a bear market,

31
00:01:06,960 --> 00:01:09,720
when prices have dropped more than 20%.

32
00:01:09,720 --> 00:01:12,180
Since 1932, these bear markets

33
00:01:12,180 --> 00:01:14,310
have popped up on average every four

34
00:01:14,310 --> 00:01:15,450
years and eight months.

35
00:01:15,450 --> 00:01:17,670
They tend to keep dragging the market down

36
00:01:17,670 --> 00:01:22,440
for about 289 days, or roughly 9.6 months.

37
00:01:22,440 --> 00:01:24,630
Sure, that sounds like a long time,

38
00:01:24,630 --> 00:01:26,670
but keep in mind that bull markets,

39
00:01:26,670 --> 00:01:28,770
which is when the market is going up,

40
00:01:28,770 --> 00:01:33,540
usually last around 965 days or 2.6 years.

41
00:01:33,540 --> 00:01:36,090
The third type is a stock market collapse,

42
00:01:36,090 --> 00:01:38,640
which I class as an over 30% drop

43
00:01:38,640 --> 00:01:39,840
in the stock market,

44
00:01:39,840 --> 00:01:42,450
normally within a very
short amount of time,

45
00:01:42,450 --> 00:01:45,540
although these are very
uncommon, they can happen.

46
00:01:45,540 --> 00:01:48,450
In my opinion, if Trump had been unalived,

47
00:01:48,450 --> 00:01:50,910
then this could have been
a very real scenario.

48
00:01:50,910 --> 00:01:53,580
That isn't a political
view, just a logical one

49
00:01:53,580 --> 00:01:55,500
due to the way the stock market reacts

50
00:01:55,500 --> 00:01:56,550
to this kind of thing.

51
00:01:56,550 --> 00:01:58,530
The main takeaway from all of this

52
00:01:58,530 --> 00:02:01,110
is that if you aren't
ready for the stock market

53
00:02:01,110 --> 00:02:02,430
to go down sometimes,

54
00:02:02,430 --> 00:02:04,800
then you shouldn't be investing in stocks.

55
00:02:04,800 --> 00:02:07,380
So how do you spot a market crash?

56
00:02:07,380 --> 00:02:10,740
Well, let's discuss the free
phases of a market crash

57
00:02:10,740 --> 00:02:12,750
so you'll know what to look out for.

58
00:02:12,750 --> 00:02:16,530
I'll also share the strategies
I use at each stage backed

59
00:02:16,530 --> 00:02:19,410
by real life examples from my experience.

60
00:02:19,410 --> 00:02:22,470
This way you'll be better
prepared than most investors.

61
00:02:22,470 --> 00:02:24,570
Remember, I'm not a financial advisor,

62
00:02:24,570 --> 00:02:26,280
and this isn't financial advice.

63
00:02:26,280 --> 00:02:28,620
I'm just sharing what's
worked for me over the years.

64
00:02:28,620 --> 00:02:31,140
Number one, the euphoria phase.

65
00:02:31,140 --> 00:02:33,960
This is a stage where
the market is at its peak

66
00:02:33,960 --> 00:02:36,420
and irrational excitement drives prices

67
00:02:36,420 --> 00:02:39,030
to unsustainable levels.

68
00:02:39,030 --> 00:02:42,420
During this stage, everyone
is happy and flying high.

69
00:02:42,420 --> 00:02:44,940
When I start seeing this blind happiness,

70
00:02:44,940 --> 00:02:46,380
I prepare my investments

71
00:02:46,380 --> 00:02:48,990
for when everything comes
crashing back to reality.

72
00:02:48,990 --> 00:02:51,720
Before the 2008 financial crisis,

73
00:02:51,720 --> 00:02:53,820
there was a couple of
things that I noticed

74
00:02:53,820 --> 00:02:56,730
that really made me
cautious about investing.

75
00:02:56,730 --> 00:02:59,520
First was the boom in consumer spending.

76
00:02:59,520 --> 00:03:00,900
Everyone had money.

77
00:03:00,900 --> 00:03:04,140
They were spending thousands
and the economy was thriving.

78
00:03:04,140 --> 00:03:07,380
A more recent example
of this is the NFT craze

79
00:03:07,380 --> 00:03:08,880
a couple of years ago.

80
00:03:08,880 --> 00:03:11,190
Never in a million years
would I have thought

81
00:03:11,190 --> 00:03:13,770
that people would buy JPEG image files

82
00:03:13,770 --> 00:03:15,540
for millions of dollars.

83
00:03:15,540 --> 00:03:17,400
Things like this are a clear sign

84
00:03:17,400 --> 00:03:19,500
of too much money in circulation.

85
00:03:19,500 --> 00:03:23,040
The second thing I noticed
in 2008 was the increase

86
00:03:23,040 --> 00:03:27,210
in the number of people
buying houses or refinancing.

87
00:03:27,210 --> 00:03:29,970
This is because it was easier
than ever to get credit

88
00:03:29,970 --> 00:03:32,010
as the housing market was booming,

89
00:03:32,010 --> 00:03:34,980
which meant if people were
unable to pay their mortgages,

90
00:03:34,980 --> 00:03:36,450
then the banks could take back

91
00:03:36,450 --> 00:03:38,730
the properties without losing any money.

92
00:03:38,730 --> 00:03:40,980
Now, it's one thing
noticing these little clues,

93
00:03:40,980 --> 00:03:43,350
but it's another thing
actually taking action

94
00:03:43,350 --> 00:03:44,700
and preparing yourself.

95
00:03:44,700 --> 00:03:48,690
Between 2007-08, I could have
just gone along with the crowd

96
00:03:48,690 --> 00:03:52,050
as the general herd mentality
was that everything was great

97
00:03:52,050 --> 00:03:54,450
and nothing would ever go wrong.

98
00:03:54,450 --> 00:03:57,360
But instead, I started
to prepare my investments

99
00:03:57,360 --> 00:03:58,200
for the worst.

100
00:03:58,200 --> 00:03:59,970
At the time, lots of my friends

101
00:03:59,970 --> 00:04:02,430
and fellow business owners
didn't quite understand

102
00:04:02,430 --> 00:04:04,290
the decisions I was making.

103
00:04:04,290 --> 00:04:07,410
They may have even seen
me as a bit of a coward,

104
00:04:07,410 --> 00:04:09,300
but from my perspective,

105
00:04:09,300 --> 00:04:10,410
I don't think they understood

106
00:04:10,410 --> 00:04:12,240
how much risk they were taking.

107
00:04:12,240 --> 00:04:15,450
So if your spidey senses start tinkling,

108
00:04:15,450 --> 00:04:17,250
these are some of the things you can do

109
00:04:17,250 --> 00:04:19,050
to prepare yourself for the worst.

110
00:04:19,050 --> 00:04:20,760
First, I would evaluate

111
00:04:20,760 --> 00:04:24,000
and minimize your risk
level wherever possible.

112
00:04:24,000 --> 00:04:27,660
Personally, I'm not focused
on chasing crazy high returns

113
00:04:27,660 --> 00:04:30,450
as that's unsustainable for the long term.

114
00:04:30,450 --> 00:04:33,240
I just wanna be making
reasonable gains consistently

115
00:04:33,240 --> 00:04:34,890
so my money compounds.

116
00:04:34,890 --> 00:04:38,310
I always think about the story
of the tortoise and the hare.

117
00:04:38,310 --> 00:04:39,660
I know it might sound boring,

118
00:04:39,660 --> 00:04:41,370
especially coming from a boomer,

119
00:04:41,370 --> 00:04:43,770
but slow and steady does win the race.

120
00:04:43,770 --> 00:04:45,120
If you're new to investing,

121
00:04:45,120 --> 00:04:47,130
there's a high chance
you haven't experienced

122
00:04:47,130 --> 00:04:48,660
a real market crash.

123
00:04:48,660 --> 00:04:50,070
It can be horrifying

124
00:04:50,070 --> 00:04:53,520
to see your portfolio
completely halving in value

125
00:04:53,520 --> 00:04:56,730
and sitting deep in the red
for a brief period of time.

126
00:04:56,730 --> 00:04:59,640
So you have to ask yourself
if you could mentally handle

127
00:04:59,640 --> 00:05:02,100
this kind of drop without
selling your investment.

128
00:05:02,100 --> 00:05:05,130
Secondly, I would start
to reduce my leverage.

129
00:05:05,130 --> 00:05:07,890
Now, on one hand, leverage is a great way

130
00:05:07,890 --> 00:05:11,760
to accelerate wealth, but it
can also be very dangerous.

131
00:05:11,760 --> 00:05:14,850
The thing is, if a stock crashed too far,

132
00:05:14,850 --> 00:05:18,030
then your investing platform
may issue a margin call,

133
00:05:18,030 --> 00:05:20,130
which means you have a
limited amount of time

134
00:05:20,130 --> 00:05:21,420
to pay off your debts,

135
00:05:21,420 --> 00:05:24,240
and if you don't, your
brokerage may sell your stocks

136
00:05:24,240 --> 00:05:25,710
at the bottom of the market

137
00:05:25,710 --> 00:05:27,390
to recover the money you borrowed.

138
00:05:27,390 --> 00:05:29,070
If this is something you're considering

139
00:05:29,070 --> 00:05:31,590
or even doing, then if I were you,

140
00:05:31,590 --> 00:05:33,540
I would be paying some of this debt off.

141
00:05:33,540 --> 00:05:36,720
I never use margin, but
that's a personal choice,

142
00:05:36,720 --> 00:05:40,020
and I'm well aware that by
not taking on this risk,

143
00:05:40,020 --> 00:05:42,540
I'm missing out on some potential profits.

144
00:05:42,540 --> 00:05:44,550
The truth is I've seen too many

145
00:05:44,550 --> 00:05:46,203
of my friends go from millionaire status

146
00:05:46,203 --> 00:05:48,660
to broke in a blink of an eye.

147
00:05:48,660 --> 00:05:50,880
And now I just stay well clear of it.

148
00:05:50,880 --> 00:05:53,370
Thirdly, I'd start saving some extra cash

149
00:05:53,370 --> 00:05:55,440
in a high interest savings account.

150
00:05:55,440 --> 00:05:57,960
I know I bang on about
having an emergency fund

151
00:05:57,960 --> 00:06:00,150
of three to five months
of your living expenses,

152
00:06:00,150 --> 00:06:03,870
but I'm talking about saving even more.

153
00:06:03,870 --> 00:06:06,720
I did this between 2007-08.

154
00:06:06,720 --> 00:06:09,150
From the outside, it looked a bit strange.

155
00:06:09,150 --> 00:06:10,530
The market was booming,

156
00:06:10,530 --> 00:06:12,180
and by leaving my money in the bank,

157
00:06:12,180 --> 00:06:14,400
I wasn't taking advantage of it.

158
00:06:14,400 --> 00:06:16,350
However, I noticed that more

159
00:06:16,350 --> 00:06:19,200
and more people were getting
interested in investing,

160
00:06:19,200 --> 00:06:21,630
which tipped me off that there was a bit

161
00:06:21,630 --> 00:06:22,830
of a bubble forming.

162
00:06:22,830 --> 00:06:25,290
You see, when everyone
starts getting comfortable

163
00:06:25,290 --> 00:06:26,760
with the idea of investing,

164
00:06:26,760 --> 00:06:27,630
it can be a sign

165
00:06:27,630 --> 00:06:31,470
that things are about to pop
as pricing is being propped up

166
00:06:31,470 --> 00:06:33,420
by inexperienced investors.

167
00:06:33,420 --> 00:06:36,540
The trouble is that at
the first sign of a crash,

168
00:06:36,540 --> 00:06:38,520
lots of these people panic sell,

169
00:06:38,520 --> 00:06:41,250
which drives the prices down even further,

170
00:06:41,250 --> 00:06:43,170
leading to a spiral of doom.

171
00:06:43,170 --> 00:06:44,700
Finally, in this stage,

172
00:06:44,700 --> 00:06:47,910
I would make sure my investments
were properly spread out.

173
00:06:47,910 --> 00:06:50,130
This is called diversification,

174
00:06:50,130 --> 00:06:51,420
and it's one of the best ways

175
00:06:51,420 --> 00:06:54,810
to help withstand a market
crash as quite simply per,

176
00:06:54,810 --> 00:06:57,060
you haven't got all
your eggs in one basket.

177
00:06:57,060 --> 00:06:58,860
This is all because you never know

178
00:06:58,860 --> 00:07:01,440
what sector is gonna be hit the hardest.

179
00:07:01,440 --> 00:07:02,790
During the good times,

180
00:07:02,790 --> 00:07:04,410
it can be very common for people

181
00:07:04,410 --> 00:07:06,930
to do very well with one or two stocks

182
00:07:06,930 --> 00:07:09,240
and end up with most
of their money focused

183
00:07:09,240 --> 00:07:11,370
in only a couple of different companies.

184
00:07:11,370 --> 00:07:14,250
Even if they start out with
lots of different stocks,

185
00:07:14,250 --> 00:07:15,390
it can almost seem silly

186
00:07:15,390 --> 00:07:18,060
to put your money into
other things when one stock

187
00:07:18,060 --> 00:07:19,770
outperforms all your others.

188
00:07:19,770 --> 00:07:23,130
Let's use some of my favorite
stocks as an example.

189
00:07:23,130 --> 00:07:25,440
Say you have a thousand dollars to invest.

190
00:07:25,440 --> 00:07:29,040
Now, you could put all of
that into Tesla with the hopes

191
00:07:29,040 --> 00:07:30,600
of it going to the moon,

192
00:07:30,600 --> 00:07:34,230
but if Tesla gets hit the
hardest in a market crash,

193
00:07:34,230 --> 00:07:36,330
it won't be great news for your money.

194
00:07:36,330 --> 00:07:39,810
Whereas investing into a total
US stock market fund would

195
00:07:39,810 --> 00:07:42,810
spread your money across
multiple different industries.

196
00:07:42,810 --> 00:07:45,648
Look, nobody can predict if
the stock market's gonna go up

197
00:07:45,648 --> 00:07:47,520
or continue downwards.

198
00:07:47,520 --> 00:07:51,630
However, diversifying goes
some way to reducing your risk.

199
00:07:51,630 --> 00:07:53,730
Yes, you can't guarantee returns,

200
00:07:53,730 --> 00:07:56,640
but at least you're investing
in a broad range of sectors.

201
