227
00:09:01,110 --> 00:09:03,540
Number two, the reckoning phase.

228
00:09:03,540 --> 00:09:06,960
I like to call this as
everyone gets rudely punched

229
00:09:06,960 --> 00:09:08,580
in the face with the truth

230
00:09:08,580 --> 00:09:11,760
and only the ones that know
how to navigate it will be able

231
00:09:11,760 --> 00:09:14,280
to hold their nerve and make some money.

232
00:09:14,280 --> 00:09:16,080
This is the phase where the reality

233
00:09:16,080 --> 00:09:18,240
of overvaluation sets in,

234
00:09:18,240 --> 00:09:21,000
triggering widespread panic and sell offs.

235
00:09:21,000 --> 00:09:23,130
What I'm trying to get
at is in this phase,

236
00:09:23,130 --> 00:09:25,920
the stock market just comes tumbling down

237
00:09:25,920 --> 00:09:28,560
and it's next to impossible
to be unaffected.

238
00:09:28,560 --> 00:09:31,860
Even my son knew something
was happening in 2008

239
00:09:31,860 --> 00:09:33,000
and he was only 10.

240
00:09:33,000 --> 00:09:35,078
The number of customers that came

241
00:09:35,078 --> 00:09:36,510
into my hobby stores halved overnight,

242
00:09:36,510 --> 00:09:38,190
and even when they did come in,

243
00:09:38,190 --> 00:09:39,750
they didn't spend anything.

244
00:09:39,750 --> 00:09:40,890
on the bright side,

245
00:09:40,890 --> 00:09:43,080
I had lots of products which I owned,

246
00:09:43,080 --> 00:09:44,850
and my warehouses were full.

247
00:09:44,850 --> 00:09:48,300
It was sort of a bit like a
safety blanket, I suppose.

248
00:09:48,300 --> 00:09:52,380
In 2008, I saw dollar stores
opening up everywhere.

249
00:09:52,380 --> 00:09:55,320
It was the perfect mixture
of demand for cheap goods

250
00:09:55,320 --> 00:09:58,050
and supply of products
from failing businesses.

251
00:09:58,050 --> 00:10:00,810
Even if you manage to predict
all the signs of the crash

252
00:10:00,810 --> 00:10:03,120
and in phase one prepared correctly,

253
00:10:03,120 --> 00:10:06,090
phase two is really where you get tested.

254
00:10:06,090 --> 00:10:08,280
It's more about human psychology

255
00:10:08,280 --> 00:10:10,200
as most people's initial reaction

256
00:10:10,200 --> 00:10:13,200
is to sell their investments
and cut their losses.

257
00:10:13,200 --> 00:10:15,000
You need to seriously ask yourself,

258
00:10:15,000 --> 00:10:17,550
what are you gonna do
when the market goes down?

259
00:10:17,550 --> 00:10:19,980
Everyone says they're long-term investors

260
00:10:19,980 --> 00:10:21,690
until the market crashes.

261
00:10:21,690 --> 00:10:23,850
It's very easy to be a long-term investor

262
00:10:23,850 --> 00:10:25,020
while everything's going up.

263
00:10:25,020 --> 00:10:26,670
If you believe in your investments,

264
00:10:26,670 --> 00:10:28,290
then you have to hold firm.

265
00:10:28,290 --> 00:10:29,700
To have this kind of belief,

266
00:10:29,700 --> 00:10:32,970
you need to know why you
invested in something.

267
00:10:32,970 --> 00:10:35,940
That's why it's so important
to understand the fundamentals

268
00:10:35,940 --> 00:10:38,550
of a company before
investing in their stock.

269
00:10:38,550 --> 00:10:41,520
This reminds me of a story
Peter Lynch once shared.

270
00:10:41,520 --> 00:10:43,080
He's a well-known investor,

271
00:10:43,080 --> 00:10:46,380
and back in the day he bought
shares in Kaiser Industries

272
00:10:46,380 --> 00:10:48,390
when they dropped significantly.

273
00:10:48,390 --> 00:10:53,190
The company had zero debt
making bankruptcy very unlikely.

274
00:10:53,190 --> 00:10:56,370
He thought to himself,
how much lower can it go?

275
00:10:56,370 --> 00:10:59,340
But the price kept dropping to under $10.

276
00:10:59,340 --> 00:11:00,330
He was shocked,

277
00:11:00,330 --> 00:11:01,163
but held on

278
00:11:01,163 --> 00:11:04,770
and the stock eventually rebounded to $50.

279
00:11:04,770 --> 00:11:07,860
The point is, if you don't
understand the company,

280
00:11:07,860 --> 00:11:10,260
what will you do when
the stock keeps dropping?

281
00:11:10,260 --> 00:11:13,080
Probably sell and lose
out on potential gains.

282
00:11:13,080 --> 00:11:15,630
This applies to index
fund investors as well.

283
00:11:15,630 --> 00:11:18,060
A study by Fidelity actually found out

284
00:11:18,060 --> 00:11:22,950
that if you invested $10,000
in a simple S&P 500 index fund

285
00:11:22,950 --> 00:11:25,620
between the 1st of January, 1980,

286
00:11:25,620 --> 00:11:27,930
and the 31st of December, 2022,

287
00:11:27,930 --> 00:11:31,440
you would have $1,082,009.

288
00:11:31,440 --> 00:11:34,470
But if you decided to
sell your investments

289
00:11:34,470 --> 00:11:37,860
and ended up missing the
five best trading days,

290
00:11:37,860 --> 00:11:42,330
then you would only have $671,051.

291
00:11:42,330 --> 00:11:44,760
The crazy thing is that missing out

292
00:11:44,760 --> 00:11:47,250
just 50 of the best trading days

293
00:11:47,250 --> 00:11:51,330
brings you all the way down to $76,104.

294
00:11:51,330 --> 00:11:53,640
So you might think you are being smart

295
00:11:53,640 --> 00:11:55,080
by time in the market,

296
00:11:55,080 --> 00:11:56,490
but in the long run,

297
00:11:56,490 --> 00:11:58,770
you're probably only gonna
hurt your own profits.

298
00:11:58,770 --> 00:12:01,050
But if you believe in your
stocks for the long term,

299
00:12:01,050 --> 00:12:04,200
there is a lot more to it
than just holding firm.

300
00:12:04,200 --> 00:12:07,680
In 2008, I saw what the
dollar stores were doing,

301
00:12:07,680 --> 00:12:11,580
and instead of seeing a
competitor, I saw an opportunity.

302
00:12:11,580 --> 00:12:13,920
If they could buy things
for a bargain price,

303
00:12:13,920 --> 00:12:16,740
then it must mean there were
amazing deals available.

304
00:12:16,740 --> 00:12:18,600
So I went out hunting.

305
00:12:18,600 --> 00:12:21,300
I went on a bit of a buying
spree over the next couple

306
00:12:21,300 --> 00:12:23,430
of years and acquired
lots of different assets,

307
00:12:23,430 --> 00:12:26,820
including stocks and
even entire businesses.

308
00:12:26,820 --> 00:12:30,360
I knew that I would be unable
to time the exact bottom

309
00:12:30,360 --> 00:12:33,090
of the market, so I invested every week.

310
00:12:33,090 --> 00:12:35,160
This is called dollar cost averaging.

311
00:12:35,160 --> 00:12:36,810
Cash is really king.

312
00:12:36,810 --> 00:12:37,920
If you have cash,

313
00:12:37,920 --> 00:12:41,130
you can snap up some amazing
investments during this time.

314
00:12:41,130 --> 00:12:44,430
That's why it's super important
to keep a steady income

315
00:12:44,430 --> 00:12:46,650
and supercharge it with a side hustle

316
00:12:46,650 --> 00:12:48,180
during times like these,

317
00:12:48,180 --> 00:12:50,310
as the more assets you can invest in,

318
00:12:50,310 --> 00:12:53,130
the better you'll probably end
up doing in the next phase.

319
00:12:53,130 --> 00:12:55,800
The bottom line here is that
while some choose to panic

320
00:12:55,800 --> 00:12:57,570
sell and lose all their money,

321
00:12:57,570 --> 00:13:00,120
others choose to double
down and buy the dip,

322
00:13:00,120 --> 00:13:01,470
which you've done correctly,

323
00:13:01,470 --> 00:13:03,180
can make you a fortune.

324
00:13:03,180 --> 00:13:06,090
I feel like I should also
mention that some investors like

325
00:13:06,090 --> 00:13:08,910
to short stocks, which
is basically betting

326
00:13:08,910 --> 00:13:10,410
that a stock will go down.

327
00:13:10,410 --> 00:13:12,420
It's not something I personally do.

328
00:13:12,420 --> 00:13:15,330
However, people like
Michael Burry have been very

329
00:13:15,330 --> 00:13:17,430
successful with his strategy.

330
00:13:17,430 --> 00:13:19,260
If you want to know more about this,

331
00:13:19,260 --> 00:13:20,910
then let me know in the comments.

332
00:13:20,910 --> 00:13:22,560
I also recommend "The Big Short"

333
00:13:22,560 --> 00:13:24,630
if you feel like watching an entertaining

334
00:13:24,630 --> 00:13:26,580
and informative investing film.

335
00:13:26,580 --> 00:13:29,010
Number three, the Phoenix phase.

336
00:13:29,010 --> 00:13:31,770
In this final phase, the
market begins to recover

337
00:13:31,770 --> 00:13:35,070
and rebuild rising from
the ashes of the crash.

338
00:13:35,070 --> 00:13:38,490
It usually pushes above and
beyond the last market highs.

339
00:13:38,490 --> 00:13:39,960
I noticed that four years

340
00:13:39,960 --> 00:13:42,420
after the 2008 crisis happened,

341
00:13:42,420 --> 00:13:46,530
just after the London Olympics,
things started to improve.

342
00:13:46,530 --> 00:13:47,970
Businesses were hiring

343
00:13:47,970 --> 00:13:50,700
and money was a bit easier to come by,

344
00:13:50,700 --> 00:13:53,190
but even though people
started to have cash again,

345
00:13:53,190 --> 00:13:56,550
the mentality of not spending
carried through for a while,

346
00:13:56,550 --> 00:13:58,320
so it was another four years really

347
00:13:58,320 --> 00:14:00,210
until everything was back to normal.

348
00:14:00,210 --> 00:14:01,980
I've experienced a lot of crashes.

349
00:14:01,980 --> 00:14:04,740
I'm talking Black Monday, the.com bubble,

350
00:14:04,740 --> 00:14:09,180
the 2008 Financial Crisis
and the 2020 pandemic.

351
00:14:09,180 --> 00:14:11,460
One of the key lessons
I took from all of this

352
00:14:11,460 --> 00:14:15,420
was that a bull market almost
always follows a bear market,

353
00:14:15,420 --> 00:14:18,600
and that the seeds of your
fortune are often sown in times

354
00:14:18,600 --> 00:14:20,940
of crisis and uncertainty.

355
00:14:20,940 --> 00:14:23,580
As long as able to
handle your level of risk

356
00:14:23,580 --> 00:14:26,370
and you're buying into the
stock market consistently

357
00:14:26,370 --> 00:14:28,530
with a diversified portfolio,

358
00:14:28,530 --> 00:14:30,300
then you stand a much better chance

359
00:14:30,300 --> 00:14:32,340
than most at making some real money.

